<br>
It also depends on the type of spin you put on it.<br>
<br>
Frankly if these rotations are trivial (and they are to people like Dazz) then why does he bother doing them?  If he, and others like him, are simply out for adventure and the thrill of taking a target down fast, then why does he go after trivial targets?<br>
<br>
Because he is a bully.<br>
<br>
No matter how you spin it, thats the bottom line.  There are dozens of targets he could go after.  He could race others for the Queen in Chardok, or THO, or IV, or Terris Thule, or any of a dozen different named across the lands.  But they dont.<br>
<br>
Why?<br>
<br>
Again, because those ARE challenges.  Plus, the Kunark Dragons and mobs like Zlandicar drop loot he can sell for 150kpp+.  Because he, and others like him, are only out for themselves.  They could care less who they hurt because they think they are strong and others are weak.  Sound familier.  It sure does to me.  It reminds me of that guy who always beat up the members of the chess team because he could.  He sounds like that guy who thought of himself as the ruler of the school because he was the biggest guy out there.<br>
<br>
Well, it wasnt right in school, and it sure as hell isnt right here in EQ.<br>
<br>
There are dozens of mobs that are challenges.  There are dozens of mobs that drop items better than these rotational mobs.  There are dozens of places anyone can go to for a challenge.<br>
<br>
The only reason to grab rotation targets out of order is to be a bully and because you cant handle a real challenge.<br>
<br>
No matter how its prettied up, its all the same.  You want a challenge, take out Vindi with 1 group.  It can and has been done.  You want a challenge, do the same to Dain 425 or AoW.  You want a challenge, do Rhag 1-IV.  You want a challenge head on down and do the Burrower cycle with a single group or two.  But dont tell me taking out any of the non-Velious+ mobs is a challenge and therefor thats why your doing it.<br>
<br>
As for any other arguments, go to another server.  If FFA is all its cracked up to be and you are that good, then re-equiping yourself shouldnt be a problem should it?  I mean, it should be easy to make a few friends and go out and kill a few dozen mobs and get your stuff back right?<br>
<br>
Oh wait.  You cant do that because the real uber guilds on all the other servers keep all the good mobs perma killed from Fear mini's on up.<br>
<br>
Oh yes, and guilds like Fires of Heaven or Unity or Afterlife do contain half the server.  Every server with the exception of Karana has a guild that can field upwards of 500 people.  There is only 1 server where small guilds do more than simply serve as farm guilds for the uber guilds.  Only 1 server where you can see your epic mob even once a year.  The grass always seems greener next door, but I can assure you its painted.<br>
<br>
Frankly though, it all comes down to respect.  Do you respect others regardless of whether they are worthy of it or reciprocate it?<br>
<br>
Let me explain something quickly.<br>
<br>
No one remembers who founded The Haven or Ash or Grey Hawke or Valoran or Fama Volat or Blue Ribbon other than its members.  No one remembers The Combine other than a few old timers.  No one knows many of the guild leaders of most guilds.  Hell, most dont even know many of the guilds on the server.<br>
<br>
Close to half or more of the server knows who Haemish was.<br>
<br>
Even though he hasnt played the game in well over a year.  They remember.<br>
<br>
Why?  Because both the Silver Daggers and KCoG were his legacy.  It was founded upon respect of others and fairness always.<br>
<br>
I'm sure you could say it doesnt really matter as its just a game and who cares what others think of you in 10 years.  And to an extent thats true.  But then, who cares about honor and integrity and sense of duty?  Those things too only really mean anything to you.  And yet they too are important because they are what define you.  When you are true to yourself others recognize that and respect it.<br>
<br>
And in the end thats what people like Dazz and Zfalcon simply cant stand.  They cannot stand, as the bully in school couldnt, seeing others being better than themselves simply by helping others.  They understood at a deeper level that strength of character was something they couldnt beat and they resented that in those that had it.<br>
<br>
Call it whatever you like, but I ask this of everyone here.<br>
<br>
What will your legacy be? Will it be one of tolerance and respect to others?  Or will it simply be one of selfishness and greed.<br>
<br>
The choice is yours and yours alone.  No one can make it for you or force it upon you.  <br>
<br>
Yes, I admit I feel jealous and even hate it when people start linking items I dont have and want and will never see because I choose my path.  I hate it when I see a druid walking around offering to sell a Cowl of Mortality.  I hate knowing I've never had more than 3kpp in the bank because I dont farm and pass on rolls in favor of others who might use it.<br>
<br>
But.<br>
<br>
Then I walk into a strange zone with my friends and my guild.  And we are greeted by those we dont even know or remember fondly.  People are willing to share their camp spots with us and invite us into their groups.  We dont know them, but they remember us.  We go where we will and people know that we stand for something greater than ourselves.  And in the end, thats what matters to me.<br>
<br>
One day when I leave EQ people will remember me.  People who I never met, people who didnt know me really.  People will remember my guild and KCoG and smile.  When I leave EQ I will leave knowing I made the EQ experience better for many people and never by stepping on someone else.  There are many other people, on the other side of these monitors, who will remember.  And I will have made a difference.<br>
<br>
Now what does all this have to do with the KGC?  Pretty much nothing, except that it all starts with you.  Dont worry what others think.  Dont worry about what others do.  Worry only about what you are doing.  Everything else will take care of itself.<br>
<br>
Be fair, respect others, and do the right thing even if its not the right thing for you, and even the KGC will begin to make sense.<br>
<br>
Dont, and you simply become part of the problem instead of the solution.<br>
<br>
The choice is yours.  What will you stand for?<br>
 <p>Kellory Silverstar<br>
The Watchmen<br>
KCoG Plane Raid Liason - Retired<br>
